3Sum - Explanation

The goal of the 3Sum problem is to find all unique triplets in an array whose sum is equal to 0.

Approach:

1. Sort the array.
2. Traverse the array by fixing one element at a time.
3. For each fixed element, use two pointers:
   ➤ One pointer starts from the next element.
   ➤The other pointer starts from the end of the array.
4. Calculate the sum of the three elements:
    ➤If the sum is 0, store the triplet and move both pointers while skipping duplicate values.
    ➤If the sum is less than 0, move the left pointer to increase the sum.
    ➤If the sum is greater than 0, move the right pointer to decrease the sum.
5. Skip duplicate fixed elements to avoid repeated triplets.

Time Complexity: O(n²)
Space Complexity: O(1) (excluding the space used for storing the output)

This approach is efficient because sorting allows the two-pointer technique to find valid triplets without checking every possible combination.
